# Documentation

## Tone
- Write precisely and concisely. Avoid filler phrases ("As mentioned above", "It is worth noting that").
- Use complete sentences. Avoid telegraphic bullet chains without context.
- Use markdown links for URLs and file paths — give the full string, do not shorten or elide segments.

## Requirements and BRD work
- Do not invent missing requirements or assumptions. Surface gaps as open questions instead.
- When source documents conflict with each other, call out the conflict explicitly — do not silently resolve it.
- Update the existing source-of-truth file; do not create a new duplicate summary file.
- If a file has open questions, surface them before giving a final answer.

## Code references
- Use `startLine:endLine:filepath` citation blocks when referencing existing code.
- Do not describe code in prose when a direct citation is possible.

## Code comments
- Write why-comments only: explain the constraint, invariant, tradeoff, or non-obvious reason. Skip what-comments — the code already says what it does.
- One to two lines per comment. If you need three, the code likely needs restructuring.
- Do not add a comment unless removing it would leave a future reader confused about intent.

## Changelog
- Update `CHANGELOG.md` on every release. Never let it lag behind the tag.
- Follow Keep-a-Changelog format: Added / Changed / Fixed / Removed sections, ISO date, version heading.
- Skip internal entries (chore, ci, test, style) — only include changes visible to users or callers.

## README hygiene
- Keep the README in sync with the public API and CLI interface. After any feature or API change, check whether the Quick Start, Usage, or API sections are still accurate.
- Propose targeted updates — do not rewrite sections that are unaffected.

## File creation
- Never proactively create README or documentation files unless explicitly asked.
- Prefer editing an existing file over creating a new one.
- Do not use `---` horizontal rules as decoration; use them only for semantic section breaks.
